    <item>
      <title>MechWarrior 5: Clans is supposed to be newbie-friendly, and I put it to the test</title>
      <author>
          Kevin Purdy
        </author>
      <link>https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2024/10/i-tried-to-get-into-mechwarrior-5-clans-as-a-newcomer-but-its-for-the-fans/</link>
      <comments>https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2024/10/i-tried-to-get-into-mechwarrior-5-clans-as-a-newcomer-but-its-for-the-fans/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">82bed2590b0d4a6f2db9febc97ad60719d2d2cc0</guid>
      <pubDate>Fri, 18 Oct 2024 21:19:50 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;         All the kit balancing, squad leading, and lore you could want, if you want it.       &lt;/p&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img width="1000" height="1000" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/TimberWolf_Huntress-1000x1000.jpg" class="intro-image absolute min-w-full min-h-full h-auto object-cover" alt="" loading="eager" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/TimberWolf_Huntress-1000x1000.jpg 1000w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/TimberWolf_Huntress-150x150.jpg 150w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/TimberWolf_Huntress-500x500.jpg 500w" sizes="(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px" /&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       Heck yeah, Timber Wolf Huntress. I have no idea what that is, but it's a great name.                &lt;span class="caption-credit mt-2 whitespace-nowrap text-xs"&gt;           Credit:                       Piranha Games                    &lt;/span&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;                                                         &lt;div class="page-anchor-wrapper"&gt;&lt;a class="" name="page-1" data-page="1" data-url="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2024/10/i-tried-to-get-into-mechwarrior-5-clans-as-a-newcomer-but-its-for-the-fans/" href="https://arstechnica.com/"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;p&gt;It is &lt;a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/maximumfun/comments/3na6mj/jjho_settled_law/"&gt;a matter of settled law&lt;/a&gt; on &lt;a href="https://maximumfun.org/podcasts/judge-john-hodgman/"&gt;the Judge John Hodgman podcast&lt;/a&gt; that people like what they like, and you can't force someone to like something. It is called the Tom Waits Principle.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I thought about that principle constantly while I was trying to open myself up to &lt;a href="https://www.mw5clans.com/"&gt;&lt;em&gt;MechWarrior 5: Clans&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. Trying to jump into this game and like it, so that I'd have some critical assessment of it, was akin to handing a friend &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Black_Rider_(album)"&gt;The Black Rider&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/em&gt;and assuming they would come back begging for more.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;From everything I can tell and what I have read, this game largely delivers on the simulation, and notably a lot of the story, that &lt;em&gt;BattleTech&lt;/em&gt;/&lt;em&gt;MechWarrior&lt;/em&gt; fans revere. &lt;em&gt;Clans&lt;/em&gt; seems very good at what it sets out to do, and I do get the sense that it is relatively accommodating to newcomers compared to other entries. It just did not, despite its stand-alone nature and alleged newcomer friendliness, convert me into a loadout tactician or stomp-and-shoot enthusiast.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;aside class="ars-sidebar"&gt;       &lt;h2&gt;Details&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Developer/Publisher:&lt;/strong&gt; Piranha Games&lt;br&gt; &lt;strong&gt;Platform:&lt;/strong&gt; Windows, Xbox X|S, PlayStation 5&lt;br&gt; &lt;strong&gt;Release Date:&lt;/strong&gt; Oct. 16, 2024&lt;br&gt; &lt;strong&gt;Rating: &lt;/strong&gt;T for Teen (13+)&lt;strong&gt;&lt;br&gt; Price: &lt;/strong&gt;$50 on PC&lt;strong&gt;&lt;br&gt; Links:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href="https://store.steampowered.com/app/2000890/MechWarrior_5_Clans/"&gt;Steam&lt;/a&gt; | &lt;a href="https://store.epicgames.com/en-US/p/mechwarrior-5-clans-e50e3a"&gt;Epic&lt;/a&gt; | &lt;a href="https://www.xbox.com/en-US/games/store/mechwarrior-5-clans/9P9FJCK32PMT/0010"&gt;Xbox&lt;/a&gt; | &lt;a href="https://store.playstation.com/en-us/concept/10006171"&gt;PlayStation&lt;/a&gt; | &lt;a href="https://mw5clans.com/"&gt;Official website&lt;/a&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;br&gt; &lt;/strong&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;/aside&gt;  &lt;figure class="ars-video"&gt;&lt;div class="relative"&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.youtube.com/embed/CKo3ZljgmnY?start=0&amp;amp;wmode=transparent"&gt;https://www.youtube.com/embed/CKo3ZljgmnY?start=0&amp;amp;wmode=transparent&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="caption mt-1 inline-flex flex-row items-stretch gap-1 text-lg leading-tight text-gray-300"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-icon bg-[left_top_5px] w-[10px] shrink-0"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-content"&gt;       Release trailer for &lt;em&gt;MechWarrior 5: Clans&lt;/em&gt;.            &lt;/div&gt;   &lt;/div&gt; &lt;/figure&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Inner Spheres, Clans, and Smoke Jaguars&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;MechWarrior&lt;/em&gt; is the game series that draws from the &lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BattleTech"&gt;&lt;em&gt;BattleTech &lt;/em&gt;universe&lt;/a&gt;, which started with a wargaming title in 1984. &lt;em&gt;MechWarrior 5: Clans &lt;/em&gt;is not an expansion or sequel to &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2019/12/how-mechwarriors-return-took-me-back-to-the-early-90s-mall-in-my-mind/"&gt;&lt;em&gt;MechWarrior 5: Mercenaries&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, or &lt;em&gt;MechWarrior 4: Mercenaries&lt;/em&gt;, or &lt;em&gt;MechWarrior Online&lt;/em&gt;. &lt;em&gt;Clans &lt;/em&gt;is a stand-alone game, one with, notably, a real story rather than some very era-specific cutscenes tagged onto combat scenarios.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;You are Jayden Smoke Jaguar, which sounds like a fourth-grade notebook idea until you read more into the &lt;em&gt;BattleTech&lt;/em&gt; lore. You and four other genetically engineered members of the Smoke Jaguar Clan will move through training, deployment, and eventually raise questions about the morality of reclaiming the Inner Sphere on behalf of your Clan's prescriptive concept of humanity. And you don't use contractions while speaking—ever.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Reviewers who made it much further into &lt;em&gt;MechWarrior&lt;/em&gt; than me, like &lt;a href="https://www.pcgamer.com/games/action/mechwarrior-5-clans-review/"&gt;PC Gamer&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="https://www.ign.com/articles/mechwarrior-5-clans-review"&gt;IGN&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href="https://www.pastemagazine.com/games/mechwarrior/mechwarrior-5-clans-carves-a-strangely-satisfying-home-from-90s-space-war-wreckage"&gt;Paste&lt;/a&gt;, seem to dig how the narrative plays out, and generally find the cutscenes and narrative dialogue top-notch. Me, after a couple missions of being told how unworthy my squad (sorry, my Star) was by a commander and having my mates remind me constantly of their one or two personality traits, I was holding down keys to skip cutscenes and mostly ignoring in-mission dialogue.&lt;/p&gt;                                                                             &lt;p&gt;Again, there's a whole lot of context to the plot dynamics I'm missing, not having any &lt;em&gt;BattleTech &lt;/em&gt;background. Voices were regularly astounded to see some form of enemy or witness some explosion, while I was focused on marching forward and learning the controls.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;div class="ars-lightbox align-fullwidth my-5"&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img decoding="async" width="640" height="360" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mechwarrior_customization-640x360.jpg" class="ars-gallery-image" alt="" loading="lazy" aria-labelledby="caption-2057342" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mechwarrior_customization-640x360.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mechwarrior_customization-300x169.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mechwarrior_customization-768x432.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mechwarrior_customization-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mechwarrior_customization-384x216.jpg 384w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mechwarrior_customization-1152x648.jpg 1152w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mechwarrior_customization-980x551.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mechwarrior_customization-1440x810.jpg 1440w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mechwarrior_customization.jpg 1920w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       All eight sections (pods) of your mech can be balanced for armor, weight, and capability, and then you also balance the whole thing. You can just hear the pen scratching on paper as you plot it all out.               &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;Credit:                        Piranha Games                   &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img decoding="async" width="640" height="360" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mechwarrior_custo2-640x360.jpg" class="ars-gallery-image" alt="" loading="lazy" aria-labelledby="caption-2057341" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mechwarrior_custo2-640x360.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mechwarrior_custo2-300x169.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mechwarrior_custo2-768x432.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mechwarrior_custo2-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mechwarrior_custo2-384x216.jpg 384w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mechwarrior_custo2-1152x648.jpg 1152w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mechwarrior_custo2-980x551.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mechwarrior_custo2-1440x810.jpg 1440w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/mechwarrior_custo2.jpg 1920w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       Each pod gets a deeper view.               &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;Credit:                        Piranha Games                   &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;h2&gt;Do you like menus?&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;I have no real issue with the core loop of &lt;em&gt;Clans&lt;/em&gt;. You've got five bio-engineered clan members, each with distinct skills. Each member pilots a BattleMech (just "mech" from here on out) that can be customized. One of your pilots might have an affinity for melee fighting, and you can cultivate that or move them down a different skill tree branch to become a lighter recon type. You, Jayden, are pretty decent at everything, so you have the blessing and curse of limitless customization.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Customization is where &lt;em&gt;MechWarrior&lt;/em&gt; heads are getting much more out of this game than I am. You eventually get to pick out a mech chassis (out of 16 available), then customize each of its "pods": left/right leg, left/right arm, left/center/right torso, and head. You make interesting choices around weight, energy, speed, armor, and firepower. You get more options as you play on, spending resources on research and achieving optional goals. And you'll see most of the things you can potentially strap onto your mech on other mechs you encounter.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;With five mechs to customize and only so much experience duking it out with other mechs in the field, the "'Mech Lab" portion of &lt;em&gt;Clans&lt;/em&gt; felt overwhelming to a newcomer. There is tutorial pointing and a gradual expansion of options, but it still felt like an impediment to the stomping, shooting, and squad tactics. Which, perhaps unsurprisingly, was also a bit overwhelming for a newcomer.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;div class="ars-lightbox align-fullwidth my-5"&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img decoding="async" width="1440" height="810" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Investigate_Waypoint_Bravo_01-1440x810.jpg" class="ars-gallery-image" alt="" loading="lazy" aria-labelledby="caption-2057345" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Investigate_Waypoint_Bravo_01-1440x810.jpg 1440w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Investigate_Waypoint_Bravo_01-300x169.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Investigate_Waypoint_Bravo_01-640x360.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Investigate_Waypoint_Bravo_01-768x432.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Investigate_Waypoint_Bravo_01-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Investigate_Waypoint_Bravo_01-2048x1152.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Investigate_Waypoint_Bravo_01-384x216.jpg 384w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Investigate_Waypoint_Bravo_01-1152x648.jpg 1152w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Investigate_Waypoint_Bravo_01-980x551.jpg 980w" sizes="(max-width: 1440px) 100vw, 1440px"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       Someone yelling at you, an objective in the distance, and a bunch of blips on radar: Welcome to the front, pilot.               &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;Credit:                        Piranha Games                   &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img decoding="async" width="640" height="360" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/BattleGrid_Commands_01-640x360.jpg" class="ars-gallery-image" alt="" loading="lazy" aria-labelledby="caption-2057343" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/BattleGrid_Commands_01-640x360.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/BattleGrid_Commands_01-300x169.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/BattleGrid_Commands_01-768x432.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/BattleGrid_Commands_01-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/BattleGrid_Commands_01-2048x1152.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/BattleGrid_Commands_01-384x216.jpg 384w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/BattleGrid_Commands_01-1152x648.jpg 1152w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/BattleGrid_Commands_01-980x551.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/BattleGrid_Commands_01-1440x810.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       It's fast to tab out and check out an overhead view of the map, along with assigning commands to other units.               &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;Credit:                        Piranha Games                   &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img decoding="async" width="640" height="360" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scanning_Salvage_02-640x360.jpg" class="ars-gallery-image" alt="" loading="lazy" aria-labelledby="caption-2057347" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scanning_Salvage_02-640x360.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scanning_Salvage_02-300x169.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scanning_Salvage_02-768x432.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scanning_Salvage_02-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scanning_Salvage_02-2048x1152.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scanning_Salvage_02-384x216.jpg 384w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scanning_Salvage_02-1152x648.jpg 1152w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scanning_Salvage_02-980x551.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scanning_Salvage_02-1440x810.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       Using your scanner prevents you from using your weapons and other systems, so add it to the list of trade-offs you're making in real time.               &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;Credit:                        Piranha Games                   &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;div class="page-anchor-wrapper"&gt;&lt;a class="record-pageview" name="page-2" data-page="2" data-url="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2024/10/i-tried-to-get-into-mechwarrior-5-clans-as-a-newcomer-but-its-for-the-fans/" href="https://arstechnica.com/"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Do you like buttons?&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;I played the combat portions of &lt;em&gt;Clans&lt;/em&gt; with a controller, and it was fine. I played it with a mouse and keyboard, and it was better. Eventually, I mapped a whole bunch of squad commands to &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2024/01/figmas-creator-micro-made-me-a-macro-pad-person-with-its-colorful-clicky-keys/"&gt;my little macro pad&lt;/a&gt; and, while not quite a full throttle and joystick, it made me feel much more involved in the combat.&lt;/p&gt;                                                      &lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;There are multiple layers to a &lt;em&gt;Clans &lt;/em&gt;battle. There is your actual movement, which can take getting used to, with your legs moving on their own trajectory while you swivel your torso. There is your squad and how they're deployed, which takes up many of your background thought cycles. And there is your mech, its heating levels, its armor condition, its speed, and everything else you set yourself up for during customization.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;Your enemies and your copilots are, well, pretty dumb. There's good variety in what you face and what you must do, but nobody besides you on the field seems to have a great sense of how verticality works or what the most important thing on the field is at that moment. Once you accept that your squad mates are powerful dummies, you'll learn to let go of your own mech a bit and spend more time nudging them around or jumping into their cockpits and taking over for a spell.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;The nature of mech combat in these games did not, after a half-dozen missions, click with me. On some level, it's interesting juggling various weapons, positioning yourself with limited movement, and directing teammates. I'm going slow, and it feels like a slog, but I could go faster if I had made a different choice during loadout. I'd just have to make somebody else the heavy.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;But it's also a crunchy simulation game, simulating machinery that does not actually exist. Everything that stands between you and your sense of capable combat is a choice made by the developers.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2 dir="ltr"&gt;Mecha culpa&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;Based on my conversations with longtime &lt;em&gt;MechWarrior&lt;/em&gt; fans and reading lots of positive reviews to figure out if there's something wrong with me, I think &lt;em&gt;MechWarrior 5: Clans &lt;/em&gt;is a very juicy offering for mech fans who have been hungry for something new (and especially something set in this Clans-coming-back period) for quite some time. I'm just not entranced as a newcomer, and I'm now thinking something like &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/threads/armored-core-6.1495426/"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Armored Core VI&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt; would be more my speed if I'm looking for rocking or possibly socking robots. I also didn't engage with multiplayer at all, so my standard dismissal of combatant AI would only half-apply there.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;By all means, though, tell me and each other how this game looks or plays to you. I was not bio-engineered for &lt;em&gt;MechWarrior (&lt;/em&gt;I mean, just look at how many contractions I use), but I can still appreciate that it looks pretty good for those who fit better into the chassis.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
